HIV/Aids: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14% in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people have been affected in the country, says health authorities.
Approximately 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
Most of the new cases were transferred through sex and marked a change from previous years.
Traditionally, HIV is spread rapidly through certain parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way had been reduced to almost zero,” said Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100 000 from year to year.
HIV infection through intercourse is an urgent issue in China's HBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but discrimination against HBTs is said to be widespread.
Due to the country's conservative values, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men sooner or later will marry women.
Many of the cases of infection are due to insufficient protection in connection with intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese Government has promised universal access to HIV medicine as part of its efforts to tackle the problem.
