What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual musical event that has a tremendously impressive display of stars performing and an equally impressive mission; to combat world poverty.
During its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people flocking to Central Parks Great Lawn, not only to enjoy artists such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the real goal of the event: to combat extreme poverty by 2030.
Global Citizen Festival, according to a 2012 statement, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international preface group that hopes to fight poverty by increasing the number of people who are actively fighting it.
In order to get a free ticket to the event (if you were not ready to pay for a VIP ticket), the concert guests would perform a series of tasks, or "actions" such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, ringing or in other meaningful ways contributing to raising awareness of the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been with 12 years to reach its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a genuine way to convince people to act, or is it only about so-called "clickivism" - people who feel that they make a real difference by signing an online application or writing an online tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen states that more than 19 million "actions" have been recorded from its supporters who have fought for a variety of goals.
It says that these actions have helped to spur world leaders to announce commitments and policies that correspond to more than 37 billion dollars, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group quoted 390 commitments and announcements arising from its actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid out or funded.
The group estimates that the accumulated assets so far have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the most important commitments are The Power of Nutrition, a partnership based in the UK between investors and stakeholders who are engaged in "helping children to develop to their full potential", promising to give Rwanda 35 million dollars to help fight malnutrition in the area after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from global citizens.
"With the support of the British Government, donors, national governments and global citizens, just like you, we can do social injustice that is subservient to history," said the ambassador to the Partnership Tracey Ullman to the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5000 measures were taken requiring the UK to improve the diet of mothers and children, the government announced funding for the project, Power of Nutrition, which includes diet programmes targeted at 5 million women and children.
In response to one of the common questions on its website: "What makes you think that we can fight extreme poverty?"
Global citizen replied: "It will be a long and difficult road - sometimes we will fall and fail.
But, as the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because we are stronger together.
