The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, World Wide Web inventor, launches a startup aimed at competing with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lees open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people are given access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee ridiculed that the intention behind Inrupt is "world domination".
"We have to do it now," he said about the start-up company.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "personal online data great" or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, to make lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify all are available in a browser at the same time.
What is unique about personal online data storage is that it is entirely up to the user who can access which type of information.
The company calls it "personal authorization through data."
The idea of Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is that the company should include resources, processes and appropriate skills to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a number of software developers to work with the project and a group of volunteer coders.
From this week onwards, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether to introduce a complete change where all business models are put on high edge overnight.
"We're not asking them for permission."
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new web created by Solid.
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Berners-Lee has in recent months been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
During the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and head of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
"I am very optimistic about this new era on the web," added Berners-Lee.
