The study, by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the South and Dwarf Piistrell as well as brown loaned and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special players will be placed in important places around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and which species do what.
A natural environment map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area view of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation advisor, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest fields for bats and other related species.
Flatdermus populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by building and development work that affects the nest and the loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting may also pose a risk, as well as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as house cat attacks.
The bats are not really blind.
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organisation has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct investigations, examine bons and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threeave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home for eight of Scotland's ten bats.
David Thompson, property manager, says the property is the ideal area for them.
"Here at Threeave we have a good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and a variety of favorable habitats.
But there is a lot about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to understand more about what they need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before carrying out maintenance within properties, as it is possible that accidental destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young people, and possibly destroy an entire population.
The bats are peaceful and it is illegal to kill, bother or disturb them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are feeling."
